If you want, I can next convert this into a short 2–3 minute verbal explanation for your client discussion.


What Spring Boot is expected to do
From the design you shared earlier, Spring Boot is not the workflow engine itself. Its role is to extract workflow changes from CMWS, normalize them into a common event format, validate them, and pass them downstream to NiFi / messaging / ELK. Since CMWS stores state in Oracle and uses workflow history tables, Spring Boot will most likely read incremental DB changes or related APIs, convert them into standardized events, and publish them onward.





How Queue Works in CMWS
Every document or case is always in one queue at a time
Movement between queues = workflow progression
Each move generates an event (captured in WORKFLOW_HISTORY)
Examples of Queues
Intake / Auto-Assign Queue → initial entry
Active Queue → being processed
Pending Queue → waiting for external input
Approval Queue → awaiting approval
Completed Queue → work finished
Exception Queue → issues requiring manual intervention
Technical Understanding
Queue data is stored in DOCUMENT_QUEUE table
Current queue
Assigned user
Queue transitions are recorded in WORKFLOW_HISTORY
















Workflow means the lifecycle of a work item in CMWS. A work item can be a document, claim, case, or request, and it moves through different states like queue, assignment, review, pending, approval, and completion. In CMWS, each business area has its own workflow instance, queues, and rules, so workflow is basically the process that controls how an item moves from one stage to another.
Event means any meaningful change in that workflow. The docs show that CMWS internally fires workflow events such as enqueue, move, reserve, assign, get-next, and inbox/queue retrieval. These are not just logs; they represent real state transitions in the workflow. For example, when an item is moved from one queue to another, or reserved by a user, that is an event. The database also records these changes in workflow history tables, so the DB becomes the source of truth for event reconstruction.
